<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCIENCE CALENDAR: HABITAT SYMPOSIUM AT CAL STATE FULLERTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NONA YATES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Habitat destruction can be linked to the decline of many plant and animal 
populations. Protection of endangered habitats is crucial to a healthy 
environment. 
</P>
<P>
The Southern California Botanists, in conjunction with the Cal State Fullerton 
Biology Department, will be sponsoring a symposium on the Management of 
Endangered Habitats on Saturday from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
The program will be held in the Ruby Gerontology Center on campus. On-site 
registration begins at 8 a.m. Call (714) 773-3548 or (714) 869-4062. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ENVIRONMENT 
</P>
<P>
The second Healing the Planet symposium will be held at the Santa Monica Civic 
Auditorium on Saturday from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Organized by the Beyond War 
Foundation, the L.A. Chapter of Physicians for Social Responsibility and UCLA 
Extension, speakers such as Barry Commoner and Petra Kelly will discuss 
economic, political and ethical issues. Call (213) 825-9971 or (818) 784-7006 
to register. 
</P>
<P>
The annual Morro Bay Field Ecology Workshop of the Sierra Club's Natural 
Science Section will be held Nov. 2-4. Call (714) 650-0654. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
SCIENCE FOR FAMILIES 
</P>
<P>
Kids can learn about the body's bone structure while creating traditional 
Halloween skeleton displays in workshops at Pasadena's Kidspace Museum on 
Wednesday at 2:30, 3:15 and 4 p.m. Call (818) 449-9144. 
</P>
<P>
Scavenger hunts, games and educational activities will highlight a family walk 
led by Santa Monica Mountains Conservancy docents in Happy Camp Park on 
Saturday at 10 a.m. Call (805) 255-0640 or (213) 456-7807. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ARCHEOLOGY 
</P>
<P>
Some of the world's finest prehistoric rock carvings, located near the desert 
community of Ridgecrest, will be the topic of a class and field trip offered by 
UCLA Extension. Archeologist Anne Duffield will present an illustrated lecture 
on Oct. 30, followed by a trip to the area on Nov. 3. Call (213) 206-8503. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
MARINE SCIENCE 
</P>
<P>
Adults and youngsters over 13 can join a research project on the spider crab 
population of the Point Fermin Marine Life Refuge in a workshop offered by the 
Cabrillo Marine Museum on Nov. 3 at 1:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
Museum naturalists will also be leading an overnight observation and collecting 
expedition to Santa Catalina Island on Nov. 2-3. Call (213) 548-7563 for 
information on both programs. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ASTRONOMY 
</P>
<P>
The amateur astronomy club of the Santa Clarita Valley will have an 
informational program on the various types of telescopes on Nov. 3 at 7 p.m. at 
the Placerita Canyon Nature Center. Call (805) 259-3284 or (818) 362-1175. 
</P>
<P>
Mt. Wilson Observatory solar astronomer Larry Webster will give a 
behind-the-scenes look at the world-renowned observatory at the Santa Monica 
College Planetarium program on Friday at 8 p.m., following the Night Sky Show 
at 7 p.m. Call (213) 452-9223. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
MEDICINE/HEALTH 
</P>
<P>
Health-care professionals will address the special concerns of pregnancy for 
women over 30 in a program at the Medical Center of North Hollywood on 
Wednesday at 7 p.m. Call (818) 753-2483. NONA YATES 
</P>
</TEXT>
