<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
EVER-PRESENT DANGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHUCK NUNLEY, Officer CHUCK NUNLEY of the Los Angeles Police Department was 
shot and wounded in April, 1984, while investigating a family dispute. He 
talked to The Times about police fears of being shot: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We do have a fear that anything can go wrong at any given point. When you are 
confronting people -- whether it be a car full of five or six gang-bangers or 
people fighting -- there is always a fear. 
</P>
<P>
I don't think there are people running around waiting to blow away police 
officers, but there is always the present danger. For us to hear of something 
like the shooting of Detective Russell Kuster affects us all personally. April, 
1984, automatically clicks in my head. 
</P>
<P>
I didn't know (Kuster), but it's still like losing a family member. We've all 
run around on that same track, done push-ups on the same field and been taught 
pretty much the same things. It's devastating, but we know we have to keep 
pushing. If we don't, this city could go to hell. Steps are being taken to help 
make sure officers aren't wounded in the line of duty. Hopefully, the new 
gun-control law that Chief (Daryl Gates) is pushing will help. We are running 
into kids on the street with much more sophisticated weapons than we have. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
